      <body>
         <div type="edition">
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/><persName type="divinity"><name key="Ἄρτεμις Artemis">Ἀρτέμιδι</name> <name key="Anaïtis Ἀναείτις">Ἀναείτι</name></persName> κ<supplied reason="lost">αὶ</supplied> <persName type="divinity"><name key="Men Μήν"><supplied reason="lost">Μη</supplied>
               <lb n="2" break="no"/>νὶ</name> <name key="Tiamou Τιάμου">Τιάμου</name></persName> <persName><name key="Musaes Μουσαῖς">Μουσαῖς</name></persName> β <supplied reason="lost">καὶ</supplied>
               <lb n="3"/><persName><name key="Καλλιγένια Kalligeneia">Καλλιγένια</name></persName> ἡ σύμβι<supplied reason="lost">ος αὐ</supplied>
               <lb n="4" break="no"/>τοῦ ὑπὲρ <persName><name key="Musaes Μουσαῖς">Μουσαίου</name></persName> το<supplied reason="lost">ῦ ὑοῦ</supplied>
               <lb n="5"/>μαρτυροῦντες τάς δ<supplied reason="lost">υνά</supplied>
               <lb n="6"/>μις τῶν θεῶν ἀπέδω<supplied reason="lost">καν</supplied>
               <lb n="7"/>τὴν εὐχήν· ἔτους σπα <supplied reason="lost"><expan><abbr>μη</abbr><ex>νὸς</ex></expan></supplied>
               <lb n="8"/>Δείου <num type="cardinal" value="1">ι</num>.
            </ab>
         </div>
         
         <div type="translation">
            <p>To Artemis Anaïtis and Men Tiamu: Musaes, son of Musaes, and Kalligeneia his consort,
               on behalf of Musaes their son, in testimony to the powers of the gods, have paid
               their vow. In the year 281, the 10th of the month Dios.</p></div>
         
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>verification: photo and MFA web entry; 2023</p>
            <p>line 2: β here is notation used to indicate that Musaes is the second generation with his name. This would make his son Musaes γ, etc. (Wright 1895)</p>
            <p>The month Δῖος---from the Macedonian calendar---would have been the first month of the year, and begun "soon after the autumnal equinox", but under the Romans the year began around August 1st. This allows for the inscription to be dated to August, 196 CE. Wright also mentions 249 AD, but this appears to be a mathematical possibility and not a good match otherwise? (Wright 1895)</p>
         </div>
